{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_rigoletto_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608774/1958052601/0965.xml":{"full_text":"A-8\nTHI EVEKINO STAR, Washington, D. C.\n\u2014pay, wat sa. isaa\nIBM\ny\nVS\u25a0 M\nI I I\ny .yy -_\u25a0 ;&0\n1\nI^Bh\nOLD ASSOCIATION RECALLED\nrormer President Harry 8. Truman visits backstage\nat the Cort Theater In New York with Ralph Bellamy\nafter the actor portrayed Franklin D. Roosevelt In\nthe play, \u201cSunrise at Campobello.\" The play deals\nwith the late President s battle with polio. Today\nMr. and Mrs. Truman sailed aboard the liner Inde\npendence on a pleasure crulte of the Mediterranean.\n\u2014AP Wlrephoto.\nCouncilman Chosen\nAs Powell Opponent\nNEW YORK, May 26 (JP). \u2014City Councilman Earl Brown\nwas chosen today as the Democratic organisation candidate to\noppose Representative Adam Clayton Powell. Jr., for the party's\nCongressional nomination.\nHis selection was announced at a meeting of district leaders\nIn Tammany Hall, headquarters,\nof the New York County Demo-1\nera tic Committee.\nMr. Brown and Mr. Powell\nare Negros. j]\nA councilman since 1950. Mr. j|\nBrown was a sponsor of the j\nlocal law banning racial dis- i\ncrimination In private housing i\nhere.\nOov. Averell Harriman tried i\nand failed over the week end to\nget two others as the party\ncandidate in the primary on\nAugust 12.\nHe unsuccessfully sought\neither Thurgood Marshall, spe\ncial counsel for the National\nAssociation for the Advance\nment of Colored People, or the\nRev. James H.. Robinson, a\nHarlem clergyman, as the Dem\nocratic candidate in the 16th\nCongressional District. Both\ndeclined tc run.\nMr. Powell has been read out j\nof the party by Tammany Hall\nand some Harlem leaders. They\nsaid their action was based on\nMr. Powell's support of Presi\ndent Eisenhower In the 1956\nelection.\nMr. Powell said he crossed\nparty lines to support the Pres\nident on the civil rights issue.\nMr. Powell is pastor of the\nAbyssinian Baptist Church of\nHarlem. He is under Federal\nIndictment on charges of in\ncome tax evasion.\nMr. Powell said yesterday on\na local radio program that al\nthough he considers himself a\nDemocrat, he would accept the\nRepublican nomination If it\nwere offered to him. However,\nhe added, he would vote In\nCongress as an independent.\nMr Powell also said: \u201cI am a\nDemocrat and I am going to\nstay one.\u201d\nO. O. P. leaders in two as- j\nsembly districts of Harlem have\nsaid they would try to get the\nRepublican nomination for Mr.\nPowell.\nMeanwhile. Mr. Powell is\nfaced with the problem of ac\nquiring the necessary signatures\nto get his name on the Demo\ncratic ballot for the August 12\nprimary.\nSOBERS\nLiberal Dividends Have been paid on regular savings fNHKiI\naccounts every year since our founding 5) years ago \u00abwHNIb\nOpen your account and start getting yours now. jt|i||fl|\nColumbia Federal\nSAVINGS LOAN ASSOCIATION jJHj\n730 Eleventh Street. N.W. REpublic 7-7111 BN|i\n1726 Penn. Ave N.W. REpublic 7-71 11\nWisconsin at Jenifer St., N.W. EMerson 3-1100\nAll\u00bbl\u00bb Ntarly SSO Million M.mb.t fSIIC C. t Krlmvir. Pr\u00bbi. r \u2022\u2014Me\n\u25a0SiKaHVfIUHKAInw\nHe told a rally at a Harlem\nchurch last night that he was\ndisturbed to learn that Oov.\nHarriman had asked Mr. Rob\ninson to run against him. Mr.\nPowell said the Oovernor had\npromised to stay out of the;\nfight.\nMr. Robinson said he felt he;\ncould not hold his church posi\ntion and accept elective office at\nthe same time.\nMr. Marshall pleaded com\nmitments in his work \"of\nNation-wide character.\u201d\nfflK FLORIDA HOME\n\"NATIONAL\nORLANDO\nMOST FREQUENT DIRECT SERVICE\nNORFOLK\nNON-STOP\nBOSTON\nNm-Stif Dinner served tMI\nM 5:30 PM camawter flifbt\nOs T fOfol Coofost later mart\u2014 tee year Travel Spent\ner phone STtrlirtf 3-5454\nNATIONAL\nAIRLINE OF THE STARS\nFederal School Aid Hit\nAs Inflationary Peril\nsr um ammisms pt*m\nThe United Stairs Chamber\nof Commerce contended today\nthat pending proposals for\nFederal aid for school construc\ntion might \u201cadd inflationary\nsteam to recovery forces once\nthey develop.\u201d\nIn testimony prepared for a\nHouse education subcommittee.\nDr. Edgar Lea Deaaen of Hatlc\nton. Pa., a member of the\nChamber's Education Commit\ntee, said school-aid measures\n\u2018cannot reasonably be advanced\nas an antl-raoeaaton measure\nThe subcommittee Is con\nsidering various propossls to\nfinance construction and oper\nating costs of public schools.\nMr. Dessen contended that\nStates and localities \u201care meet\ning their school needs without\nFederal aid and can continue\nto do so.\u201d\nHe challenged a recent Na\ntional Education Association\nsurvey which Indicated that\nsome 44.000 classrooms not'\notherwise scheduled could be'\nstarted within six months Ui\nFederal funds were made avail* 1\nable without any requirement!\nfor State or local funds.\nEighteen States, he said,\neither did not reply to the NEA\nsurvey or said no Federal funds\nwere needed, while of the 44.000\nclaasrooms which the other 30\nStates said could be started.!\n24.500 would be built in only;\nthree States, Alabama, Mlchl- 1\ngan and Pennsylvania.\nIn those three States, he said,\na Chamber of Commerce study\nAuthor Resumes Tour\nTo Aid Foundation\nMiss Ruth Nichols, author\nof the autobiography \u201cWings\nfor Life,\u201d left Washington this\nmorning on another leg of a\nNation-wide tour publicizing the\nNational Nephrosis Foundation.\nThe veteran aviatrix, who\nbegan her tour at New York\nApril 21, was scheduled to stop\nat Baltimore today.- Her tour\nas national field director for\nthe foundation, is designed to\ncall attention to work and re\nsearch in the field of nephrosis\nand related kidney diseases.\nShe came to Washington Sat\nurday morning on behalf of the\ngreater Washington Area\nChapter.\ndisclosed that school superin\ntendents did not know whether\nsites were available or whether\nplans were prepared or ap\nproved for the additional claas\nrooms.\n\u201cIn any case,\u201d he said, \u201cthe\nminimum elapsed time between\nenactment of *ederal school\nconstruction legislation and lo\ncal action would certainly be a\nyear, by which time recovery\nmight be well under way.\u201d\ntall masts...\nproud ships\nAll ere part st the\nreminiscences of dining\nml nVfVTI B\nBring your business as\nsociates and customers\nto Hogote's for lunch- 1\neon, dinner or ala carte\nspecialties in the grand\nmanner of the ship's*\ncuisine. Everything is\ncustom-cooked to your\norder. Immediate and\ngracious service.\nH-i A Best Seafood\nv in Town\nOft tht Wof\u00abrlron*\net 9th A Maine. S.W.\nin Arlington ml\n4001 Wilson Blvd.\nAMSU Sill PARKING\n1\nMemorial Day Sale\nSTURDY CANVAS OXFORDS j\nFor Sports and Outdoor Fun j r\nsiiM I*B9\nlor active fun. Rubber-soled,\nand heavy-duty toe guard.\nn ladies, white or blue, 3Vi to 9 j\nj Misses, blue or red, 12Vi to 3 j\nChildren's, blue or red, 4to 12 j\n_ _ i Teenage Favorites*Casual\nRugged Tenn.s Shoe, j Shoe, for Date, and Sport,\nfor Boys and Youths\nHigh-cut canvas tennis shoes with protec- Smartly styled flat, for Summer fun.\ntive white rubber ankle patches and toe Moccasin style with crepe sole, sporty\nc\u00bb2;3i,irwfts: 1.98\n6 1.98 of attractive colors. Well-lasted for\ncomfort in sizes 6to 9.\nWoolworth's guarantied r Picnic Needs\nLady Madison 1.00 T. Aftf\nfl Quality sunglasses with anti-infra\nWis ii j) \\WSM'-\\m/ blue or green lenses to protect eyes Pastel color packs make\n\\MI JI J from summer glare. Choice of styles, table, gayl Round plates\nvarious sizos, cups, nap-\nColton Puff Briefs j _ Papor Napkins\nSmart and Sturdy Matched Luggage j sol# C\niAn Vinyl coated covering. Gray or tan and fto 98c Value 3TC\n3 V each J.VO i Ideal for your active young\n15 overnight com 3.98* _ J playboys and girls. Perfect J 250 white or assorted pae-\nAll around pieot elastic J 21\" overnight case 4.98* JL AQ* j for the beach, too. Springy, tel paper napkins In re\nwais